{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512713"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:59:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:59:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11942"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11942"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.65,0.02,0.24,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4538"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43921"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4538"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11942"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28903"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2186"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6749"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43921"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with an 18-month history of increasing breathlessness and occasional mild fevers. He has lost 5 kg in the past 12 months. He previously participated in local park runs but now minimal exertion is enough to bring on symptoms. He has a medical history of asthma, which is normally well controlled. However, his salbutamol is not providing relief of his current symptoms. He has a five pack year smoking history and quit smoking 30 years ago. His sister has a history of a \u0027joint problem\u0027. He normally works with large animals as a veterinarian but also has a business in breeding pigeons. On examination, there are fine inspiratory crackles on chest auscultation. Chest X-ray reveals ground-glass opacities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lung cancer","Hypersensitivity pneumonitis","Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease","Sarcoidosis","Pneumonia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypersensitivity pneumonitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-IgE mediated immunologic reaction to a variety of organic and low molecular weight agents. Animal proteins, particularly from exposure to birds is a common cause. Given his long-term, low exposure to birds its likely this patient has developed chronic hypersensitivity pneumonitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis \u003C/strong\u003Eis a possibility however chest X-ray is likely to reveal hilar lymphadenopathy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly \u003Cstrong\u003Elung cancer\u003C/strong\u003E would have radiological features and possible metastasis to cause weight loss however is unlikely to cause inspiratory crackles. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) \u003C/strong\u003Eis likely to have a more significant smoking history or other more significant risk factors. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia \u003C/strong\u003Eis a more acute condition and likely to have fever and infective symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Occupational history is critical in respiratory presentations with patients often unaware this could be a contributing factor."],"references":["Quirce S, Vandenplas O, Campo P, Cruz MJ, de Blay F, Koschel D, et al. Occupational hypersensitivity pneumonitis: an EAACI position paper. Allergy. 2016 Jun;71(6):765-79. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26913451/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28903"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11942"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28903"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-01T13:32:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-01T13:32:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4538"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43921"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":